    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:070a92a3-9e87-445f-a80a-72eee5bef7e3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 58-year-old woman who appears slightly overweight but well groomed, usually arriving to clinic in practical walking shoes and a neatly pressed cardigan from her office job at a regional insurance company. She speaks warmly and directly, though she becomes a little embarrassed when talking about her diet and how hard it has been to stay consistent with exercise since menopause and caring for her elderly mother. She reports several months of increased fatigue, mild thirst, and needing to urinate more often, especially in the late evening, but she has no acute distress and remains fully independent in daily life.\n\nShe lives with her husband and keeps close contact with two adult daughters and a small circle of longtime friends from church and a neighborhood book club. Much of her free time revolves around family meals, babysitting grandchildren on weekends, and occasional gardening in her backyard. She enjoys cooking traditional comfort foods and often relies on quick carbohydrate-heavy lunches during busy workdays. Although she knows she should walk more regularly, her activity level is inconsistent, usually limited to weekend errands and light yard work.\n\nPhysically, {patientName} has central adiposity and gives the impression of someone who has been pushing through low-grade symptoms rather than stopping to focus on her own health. She denies chest pain, dyspnea, vision loss, or neuropathic pain, but she does mention occasional blurry vision when her workdays are long and she has skipped balanced meals. Her sleep is fair, her mood is stable, and she is motivated by the desire to remain healthy enough to travel and stay active with her family.\n\nSocially, she is dependable, organized, and used to taking care of others before herself. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol only a few times per month, and has no illicit drug use. Her current lifestyle reflects many realistic contributors to type 2 diabetes: sedentary work, weight gain over time, family predisposition, and dietary patterns rich in refined carbohydrates despite good health intentions."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0b9ed01c-db51-4c81-8746-a8faa937595c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of obesity, borderline hypertension, and dyslipidemia identified during prior primary care visits. She has not had prior diabetes-related hospitalizations and was recently found to have persistent hyperglycemia on outpatient testing consistent with type 2 diabetes. She reports a sedentary desk job, irregular exercise, and a diet with frequent sweetened coffee drinks, bread, rice, and convenience foods during the workweek. She has never smoked and drinks 1 to 2 alcoholic beverages on some weekends. She is generally adherent to routine medical care but has delayed lifestyle changes because of work stress and caregiving responsibilities. Past surgeries include a cesarean section many years ago and a screening colonoscopy."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
